title: For Sale/Trade:  03 turk mauser 8mm
postcontent: The 1903 is a large ring 1898 style Mauser but with a 1893 style small shank Barrel according to Olson 200000 of these were made in oberndorf between 1903 and 1905. When these were converted from their original 7.65 millimeter to 7.92 millimeter , the receiver was slightly notched to easily allow loading of the slightly longer round. The bolt and magazine of the 1903 is also shorter than an actual 8mm model 98. This is an intermediate action and the bolt and magazine are 0.2 inches shorter than a standard length 98 action. The receiver face is coincidentally 0.2 longer than a 98. Other intermediates include the M24 the Yugoslavian models 4748 and several South American contract rifles.reply by call or text is best REDACTEDRifle gets excellent 2 inch groups at 100 yards.

title: For Sale:  ARISAKA Type 99 MATCHING #s Very Mild Mod-Gloss Stock
postcontent: A low cost piece of history, once held by enemy soldiers and fired at Americans. This extremely strong design makes for a rugged, reliable and quite accurate rifle today. This is a great deer gun or a real fun range gun with history. As the previous owner decided to make it look nicer by altering the stock, it is no longer a 100% original military collectible, though unlike most Arisakas, it is a number match gun with the bolt, firing pin and front bayonet mount matching. The stock is now beautiful as compared to the semi-rough finish original. It has a gloss and is slick and smooth, plus, you can see the wood grain nicely. The rifle was cleaned so the chamber and trigger and all areas are free from gunk, dirt or anything. The MUM has been removed from the top of the receiver as almost all were making those with a MUM very desirable. Again, a full MUM would only be great on an all original gun. The letters on the top say TYPE 99. As the bores on these (non Last Ditch models) were chromed, they usually look pretty good and this one is great. Has the correct anti-aircraft rear sight though like most, the side folding wings are missing. If you want to replace them, its $12 but they were useless in WW2 and even more so now. Using bolt action rifle sights to shoot at diving and strafing aircraft?? Youd have better chances if you just point, lead and follow through like skeet. The front sight was modified by the guy too as the side ears are not there. Again, Arisaka parts are plentiful and cheap so $15 gets a whole new pin-on front sight if you want, but the current one was milled down on the sides to remove the ears, so the pin is not going to be easy to remove. The Japanese used the best sights of all rifles, a system partly copied by Steyr for their pistols. Trapezoid sighting is what Steyr calls it but the front sight is a triangle and the rear a small circular aperture. Very easy to line up and center, and for longer distance, flip the sight up, and longer distance, slide the aperture up the ladder. If you have never owned or shot one before, unless you are collecting 100% authentic items, this is a low cost way to own a piece of history. The caliber is very similar to 30-06 as most WW2 calibers were roughly equal (yes, Italy used a 6.5mm but the rest of the major players used .30 to .32 caliber rifles). Ammo is much easier to get than years ago, and if you reload, it is the best, as you can load cast bullets to reduced velocities for almost no recoil, 100 to 200 yard accuracy and low cost shooting. Or, load jacketed or low cost plated bullets for fun. I will help any buyer locate ammo if needed.  Here is the production data for this oneHowa Jyuko was the subcontractor to the Nagoya Arsenal that made the rifle. They only made one block of 50,000 rifles from 1940-1945 and started with 50,000. Since this rifle is serial number 51,952 it was most likely made in 1940.I HAVE OVER 25 PHOTOS TO SEND ANY INTERESTED PARTIESA local sale is best for this one, but if you want it shipped, I will ship to your FFL for $38Modified or sporterized Arisakas are common and usually are less than this, but most of those have had the stock cut down, and other major mods and look TERRIBLE. Look up some, you will see. Without the wood going to the front, it looks awful with the long barrel sticking out. This one looks original at first glance, and only when you notice the glossy and pretty stock do you catch on. The very front of the stock had the button for the cleaning rod release filled in and the rod is cosmetic now. I have never used one anyhow as a new $5 rod from Walmart is safer and easier than a hard steel rod.
